}}
The '''pawn''' (♙,♟) is the most numerous [[chess piece|piece]] in the game of [[chess]] and, in most circumstances, also the weakest. It historically represents [[infantry]], or more particularly, armed [[peasant]]s or [[pikemen]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://j.whyville.net/smmk/whytimes/article?id=5811|title=Chess Pieces and their Meanings|author=Titanic|website=The Whyville Times|accessdate=19 September 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt; Each player begins a game with eight pawns, one on each square of the {{chessgloss|rank}} immediately in front of the other pieces. (The white pawns start on a2, b2, c2, d2, e2, f2, g2, h2; the black pawns start on a7, b7, c7, d7, e7, f7, g7, h7.)

Individual pawns are referred to by the {{chessgloss|file}} on which they stand. For example, one speaks of &quot;White's f-pawn&quot; or &quot;Black's b-pawn&quot;. Alternatively, they can be referred to by the piece which stood on that file at the beginning of the game, e.g. &quot;White's king bishop's pawn&quot; or &quot;Black's queen knight's pawn&quot;. It is also common to refer to a ''{{chessgloss|rook's pawn}}'', meaning any pawn on the a- or h-files, a ''{{chessgloss|knight's pawn}}'' (on the b- or g-files), a ''{{chessgloss|bishop's pawn}}'' (on the c- or f-files), a ''{{chessgloss|queen's pawn}}'' (on the d-file), a ''{{chessgloss|king's pawn}}'' (on the e-file), and a ''{{chessgloss|central pawn}}'' (on the d- or e-files).
{{AN chess|pos=toc}}

==Placement and movement==
Unlike the other pieces, pawns cannot move backwards. Normally a pawn moves by advancing a single square, but the first time a pawn moves, it has the option of advancing two squares. Pawns may not use the initial two-square advance to jump over an occupied square, or to capture. Any piece immediately in front of a pawn, friend or foe, blocks its advance. In the second diagram, the pawn on c4 can move to c5; the pawn on e2 can move to either e3 or e4.

